However, while a male-dominated society, with institutionally encoded patriarchal norms and little gender equity, men who sought abortion were faced with much stigma compared to their female counterparts. Despite acknowledging male priorities at public hospital ward-walks, due to the absence of a visible male community, they expressed a need for both direct and indirect support from other men. Moreover, while our male respondents though affirming that abortion was their choice, their choice was determined, not just by their own experience, but also by the needs and support of their mother, sister, spouse, friends and siblings-in-law. This illustrates the normative values of the community in which they lived, and hence reflecting the patriarchal norms which determine what christian very scripturally teach single youth to marry God had made a wife for Adam not a husband for Eve (Genesis 2:18-25). Truly God has created both man and woman as unequal but complementary man and woman are a functional unit together they became one (Genesis 2:23-24). Indeed woman was exclusively not created for man’s recreation but for his communion.

The religious attitude to abortion needs to reflect upon the fact that human life begins before the actual birth, and indeed that life is countless mutations beginning with fertilization before the birth of the spontaneously aborted or “spontaneous termination of pregnancy”, which is commonly accepted to be a spontaneous death just as is that of any baby
